Part 1: Data

Knowing our sources

Since our data samples come from two movie critics sites. I decided to learn more about how each movie is rated on both sites respectively. It will help me understand data elements included in our sample.

IMdb [1]

IMDb (Internet Movie Database) is an online database of information related to films, television programs, home videos and video games, and internet streams, including cast, production crew and personnel biographies, plot summaries, trivia, and fan reviews and ratings.

By looking at one of its film critics, I become familiar with what IMdb can provide to our research.

Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IMDb#Film_titles

Rotten Tomatoes

Rotten Tomatoes is an American review-aggregation website for film and television. It provides top critics and user ratings.

Sample: https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_favourite_2018

Variables Included In this Dataset

There are 651 observastions. Each film (observation) has title, film metadata, director and cast awards, ratings and etc. Generalization is supported. Since there is no control group or treatment group in the experiment, causality analysis can not be conducted.

There are many categorical varialbles such as title_type and best_pic_win. So I need to be prepared for such when fitting multiple regression models.

Part 2: Research question

I want to investigate which variables are significant to movie scores. The linear model then can help us predict whether a movie will receive higher audience_score.

Each movie title has two scores, one from IMdb and one from Rotton Tomato. I pick the audience score on Rotten Tomatoes as the response variable to begin with. audience_score.

To make sure that I do not leave important information from IMdb out, I will begin my exploration with a quick look at correlations between IMdb score and Rotton Tomato scores.

The Linear Model and Anova yield to adjusted R2 of 88.48%. The selected predictor variables together can explain 88.48% of variability. There are 11.52% variability unexplained. To increase adjust R2 while preventing collinearity, I plan to use Backwards Elimination method and refine our multiple regression model.

Part 4: Modeling

My goal in this step is to finalize the minimal set of significant predictor variables to better predict audience_score.

4-1 Backwards Elimination The approach I plan to take is the step-wise backwards elimination. I will use p-value as the criteria. Each step, I will remove one predictor variable with the highest p-value. Repeating this step until I get a parsimonios model.

x<-summary(m_pass0)
y<-data.frame(x$coefficients[,4])

I followed the backwards elimination, taking out one variable with the highest p-value and then record the adjust R2 value. Such efforts should converge at the parsimonios model when adjust R2 does not fluctuate much. 
Removed Var.      Adjusted R2 Before     Adjusted R2 After
critics_score       88.48%                  88.50% 
mpaa_rating         88.50%                  88.56% 
title_type          88.56%                  88.58% 
top200_box          88.58%                  88.60%

I chose to stopped at top200_box since afterwards adjusted R2 will diminish.

4-3 MLR Diagnostics

4-3-1 Numeric variable and residuals

From my final model, I picked the numeric variable imdb_rating m_df4 <- lm(audience_score~ genre + best_actress_win + runtime + thtr_rel_year + critics_rating + imdb_rating + imdb_num_votes, data=df_ext3) 

plot(m_df4$residuals~df_ext3$imdb_rating, main='Residuals vs. IMDB rating')

Conclusion

The residuals appears to be completely random, and seem to be randomly scattered around zero.

4-3-2 Nearly Normal Residuals with Mean Zero 

hist(m_df4$residual)

qqnorm(m_df4$residual)
qqline(m_df4$residual)

Conclusion Since I do not see huge deviation from mean zero, I conclude that this condition is met.

4-3-3 Constant Variability of Residuals In this step, I want to check variability between residuals and predicted value.

plot(m_df4$residual ~ m_df4$fitted)

plot(abs(m_df4$residual) ~ m_df4$fitted)

Conclusion I do not see a fan shape here. The variability of residuals stays constant as the value of the predicted value change. So the constant variability condition is met.

4-3-4 Independent Residuals

This step is to revisit our first principle.

plot(m_df4$residuals)

Conclusion The order of x-axis and y-axis do not have obvious patterns. I can conclude that order of sample collection or time series are not considerations of the movies dataset.

Check out the 95% confidence intervalue for this case.

nralph <- data.frame(audience_score = 72, genre = "Science Fiction & Fantasy", audience_rating = "Upright", runtime = 114, thtr_rel_year = 2018, critics_rating = "Fresh", imdb_rating = 7.9, imdb_num_votes = 2678)
predict(m_df4, nralph, interval = "prediction", level = 0.95)
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 82.87664 68.50832 97.24496

Conclusions Predicted value is 11 points higher than the actual audience_score on Rotten Tomatoes. The actual score of 72 falls between the confidence intervals at 95% level.

Conclusion For documentary film (oscar winner) 20 Feet from Stardom, my model gets close to the actual rating. The predicted score is 80.7066 while the confidence interval at 95% level is 67.13 and 94.29. The actual score of 82 falls between this range.

Part 6: Conclusion

In the chosen 3 movies, the model predicts audience scores within the 95% confidence interval (see R predict results).

Shortcomings are listed below:
  1. Predicted score can be more accurate
  2. Potentially underfitting when predicting future movie titles (i.e.2018 movies) given the fact that collected movie rating samples are older than 2014
  3. Rating algorithms from two sources (IMdb and Rotten Tomatoes) can change over time, which will make this model obsolete
